Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There appears to be a superficial link between the horse with this disease in Nebraska and this horse in Kansas. The article does not tell us of any epidemiological investigation, but it is certainly circumstantial that these cases are related. It also highlights the need for extremely strict biosecurity at shows. It also should make owners think twice about taking a horse to some gathering if the horse is even slightly "off". If the animal is giving you hints it is not well, then be wise enough to put your excitement and pride on the shelf and take care of your animal, or go to the event and leave the horse to recuperate "at home".

Nebraska may be found on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2444073,229 and Kansas on the map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2444073,219. - Mod.TG]
